Makoko is in danger. Lagos isn't happy it exists. The people in power have decided they have a better use for the land and water beneath Makoko than the community it holds. They see Makoko as a slum, a scar where there could be tourism, and a place that cannot contribute to the economy because of the poor education there.

But Makoko is still a home to hundreds of thousands of people. And past relocation efforts have been less relocation and more removal with no place to go. Makoko is a community full of industry and trade. It is a place with hard-working people and little resources. We hope to bring connectivity to this community through electricity.

With our first project, we are creating a floating hackerspace/charging port for Makoko. We hope to provide the community with the resources to grow economically and intellectually. We hope to help them help themselves in the fight for their home.

Despite living in a century where we moved from 1g to 5g phone service and a time where sustainable electricity is now affordable for almost everyone everywhere. There are still communities across the world without access to internet and electricity.

Makoko is one of these places. A place where students studying for national exams are subject to the whims of an unreliable electriciy grid to study. Where sometimes students like Daniel Kalu have to wake up and study from 12am to 5am because that is the only time they have the light to study by.

By creating this floating hackerspace we hope to sustainably provide light and internet to the Makoko community for 24 hours a day. By using solar to collect energy, a battery to store it, and sustainable and easy to source materials like left-over shipping containers and pontoons from the nearby port in Lagos we can do this for less than $xx and provide a much needed resources to the community.

We've all heard the saying "There is nothing new under the sun." We agree. And yet culture after culture made and remade the wheel. Nothing is new, but no one seems to know what's already been made. That is where we step in. We are a group of students looking to connect communities to the energy solutions they need.
Instead of reinventing solutions for communities that seem to be out of the reach of energy. We aim to connect those communities with the technology to move forward.
We aim to support sustainable development for people and communities by connecting them with solutions that already exist.
We aim to support new innovations by connecting them with the people and communities that they made their creations for.

We hope our site can help connect people who need technology with the technology that already exists. We hope we can act as an equalizer for small companies who have ideas that just haven't gotten out yet.

We are creating a floating hacker space and charging port where community members can plug in to gain access to consistent electricity and internet. Because of our dedication to sustainability and simplicity we are taking advantage of materials we have at hand: pontoons and shipping containers.

Because Lagos is a port city with a trade imbalance they have excess of both of these materials just looking for a use. Using these materials reduces the need for assembly on the water and for expensive permiting for the project because both materials have already proven to be seaworthy.
Finally we hope to outfit the community center with enough solar and battery backups to ensure the location has year round power.

We have worked so hard to ensure that this project is as cheap as possible, but we're still going to need as much help from you as we can get. Our goal is (insert budget - will work w Joel on this). Anything helps!

Makoko needs this project because they are being removed from their homes. The Lagos government would rather increase tourism in the area, and Makoko isn't considered to be an economy increasing area. By empowering the people to get education, to expand business, and to become an asset to the surrounding area, they can save their homes and their livelihoods.

title: Implementing Zettelkasten in Roam: A practical guide

children.string: The goal of a Reference note is twofold:
To record the reference information of a source
To store the highlights from a source for later processing.

It’s important to remember that this is just a storage mechanism. These highlights are pretty useless on their own. It’s only when we work with these highlights that they have the potential to become something useful. This we do with Literature notes.
The goal of a Literature note is to briefly summarize a key point made in a source. You do this by:
Writing your understanding of the passage(s) in your own words
When you have a collection of Literature notes on the same topic but from different sources, then you are in a position to create a Permanent note.

Writing with a Zettelkasten feels like magic because, when you’ve accumulated enough notes, producing an outline feels instantaneous. Casual walks through your database produce more ideas than you can keep up with.

Sustainable design isn't one thing. Concepts for better or sustainable design have been created and are spreading all across the world, by academics, designers, architects, and whoever else recognizes that the world is at risk. I've found that each of these designers rejects the idea that tip-toeing across the earth is going to solve our problems. Instead, they push to create radically good things not just less bad things. To do this, they each start by developing an understanding of where they want to implement their idea. And not just a passing familiarity with the geography, the quantities of people trees or other mildly interesting phenomena in their market space - a deep understanding of how each entity they are trying to influence interacts with all other entities in the area - even ones they directly interested in. Once they know this, they establish some sort of key to determining the exact way in which they should intervene. Bjarke Ingels uses the idea of irony - what fits, but is unexpected and radically good?. The regenesis institute used decision nodes where they recognize they can have the most impact by influencing certain points. And finally - counter to many new age environmentalists none of them lose the idea that we are still ultimately designing for people. None of them believe that we are playing a zero-sum game between the earth and humans.
